a) ELS, exact line search

We first initialize all the functions initial iterate :
clear; warning("off");
Q = [4 0; 0 1]; f = @(x) (1/2)*x'*Q*x; g = @(x) Q*x; h = @(x) Q;
x = [1;2]; xk = [x]; alk = [];
k = 1;
run the algorithm:
while norm(g(x)) >= 10^-6
d = -g(x);
al = -(Q*x)'*d/(d'*Q*d); % Exact line search
x = x + al*d;
k = k+1; xk = [xk,x]; alk = [alk,al];
end
and display the iterations log:
alk = [alk,NaN];
for k=1:size(xk,2)
fprintf('k = %3i, xk =[%+5.2e, %+5.2e], ||gk|| = %+5.2e, alk = %5.3f \n',k, xk(1,k), xk(2,k),norm(g(xk(:,k))),alk(k));
end

b) BLS with W=WC (Wolfe conditions).

We first initialize all the functions initial iterate :
clear;
Q = [4 0; 0 1]; f = @(x) (1/2)*x'*Q*x; g = @(x) Q*x; h = @(x) Q;
x = [1;2]; xk = [x]; alk = [];
k = 1;
Now, the parameters for the BLS with (WC) (iW=1) are set:
almax= 1.0; almin= 0.01; rho= 0.5; c1= 0.1; c2= 0.5; iW= 1;
and the algorithm run:
while norm(g(x)) >= 10^-6
d = -g(x);
[al,iWout] = uo_BLS(x,d,f,g,almax,almin,rho,c1,c2,iW); % BLS
x = x + al*d;
k = k+1; xk = [xk,x]; alk = [alk,al];
end
Now, we display the iterations log:
alk = [alk,NaN];
for k=1:size(xk,2)
fprintf('k = %3i, xk =[%+5.2e, %+5.2e], ||gk|| = %+5.2e, alk = %5.3f \n',k, xk(1,k), xk(2,k),norm(g(xk(:,k))),alk(k));
end
k = 1, xk =[+1.00e+00, +2.00e+00], ||gk|| = +4.47e+00, alk = 0.500 k = 2, xk =[-1.00e+00, +1.00e+00], ||gk|| = +4.12e+00, alk = 0.250 k = 3, xk =[+0.00e+00, +7.50e-01], ||gk|| = +7.50e-01, alk = 1.000 k = 4, xk =[+0.00e+00, +0.00e+00], ||gk|| = +0.00e+00, alk = NaN

d) Comparison ELS vs BLS-WC vs BLS-SWC.

In view of the previous results, there is not any advantage, in this case, in using ELS. That does not mean that we don't have to use ELS whenever possible, we indeed must. Nevertheless, ELS does not guarantee to always outperform BLS.
To study a bit further this issue, let's see what happens with some larger strictly convex quadratic function:
  • First, we use function uo_sconvQF(n,seed) (see the code here) to define a strictly convex quadratic function f of dimension n=1000, its gradient g and Hessian h
clear; n=1000; seed = 1234; [f,g,h,xo]=uo_sconvQF(n,seed); Q=h(xo);
  • Now we solve the problem with ELS and display the number of iterations and execution time (using the witty command tic-toc):
x = zeros(n,1); kELS=0;
tic
while norm(g(x)) >= 10^-6
d = -g(x);
al = -g(x)'*d/(d'*Q*d); % Exact line search
x = x + al*d; kELS=kELS+1;
end
tELS=toc; kELS,tELS
kELS = 2955
tELS = 0.9882
  • Now we repeat the optimization with BLS-SWC
x = zeros(n,1); kBLS=0; almax= 1.0; almin= 0.01; rho= 0.5; c1= 0.1; c2= 0.5; iW= 2;
tic
while norm(g(x)) >= 10^-6
d = -g(x);
[al,iWout] = uo_BLS(x,d,f,g,almax,almin,rho,c1,c2,iW); % BLS
x = x + al*d; kBLS=kBLS+1;
end
tBLS=toc; kBLS,tBLS
kBLS = 666
tBLS = 2.7489
We could think that this experiment points towards discouraging using ELS, because, again, the number of iterations with ELS is much greater than with BLS-SWC. However, if we look at relation between the execution times:
tBLS/tELS
ans = 2.7817
we see that the execution time with BLS is much greater than the execution time with ELS. Actually, the relation between the time per iteration of both methods are:
(tBLS/kBLS)/(tELS/kELS)
ans = 12.3424
then, every iteration with ELS is much more faster that with BLS. That is a general behaviour and, as a rule of thumb, the greater (the nearer to 1) the slower is the BLS.

function [f,g,h,xo] = uo_sconvQF(n,seed)
rng(seed); Q=rand(n);
[V,D] = eig(triu(Q)+triu(Q)');
Q=V*diag(diag(max(D,1)))*V';
b=rand(n,1); xo = Q^-1*b;
f = @(x) x'*Q*x/2-b'*x; g = @(x) Q*x-b; h = @(x) Q;
end
